text: I went to see Madea Family Funeral Thursday night 2/28/2019. Myself and others in the movie theater laughed throughout the movie. A lot of people carry on this way during the death of a family member do to jealousy or the reading of the Will. With all the depressing things that's going on in the world today, this movie brought laughter in my life for 90 minutes. I did not like Courtney Burrell's character because he was a jerk in the movie. The Funeral Director was scary and funny.  I've noticed Tyler Perry always have attractive eye candy for the women and gay men in his movies. The women in this movie were sexy and attractive as well. Even the mother that lost her cheating no good husband was an attractive woman. I will give this movie a B+. Laughter and comedy is good for the heart and soul in today's depressing society. Joel Rush the racist white police officer in the movie plays a crooked cop Eddie Willis in the Tyler Perry series  'If Loving You Is Wrong'.

text: Hell'er, as Madea would say! I will definitely be watching Tyler Perry's "A Madea Family Funeral." This white broad loves Madea! I can't get enough of her! Tyler Perry is ingenious. He plays Madea, Joe, and Bryan and he is amazing plus his cast of characters are so hilarious, you can't help laughing from the belly! I got my sister-in-law hooked on Madea and I believe I bought every Madea project from Amazon.com and they're now on my video library there. I intend to buy "A Madea Family Funeral (2019)" when the opportunity strikes. More importantly, Tyler always has a great moral to each of his amazing stories and in every one of his projects, he mentions the name of Jesus or either Madea or one of the cast members will quote Scripture now and then. As many know, God has been pushed to the back burner or taken out all together these days. Although, there are Christian film makers, like Tyler, who promote their projects to all viewers, which is a blessing for those who wish to watch them can. I have viewed many Christian movies which are spiritually enlightening and wonderful. I watch tons of secular movies and series as well. Tyler's Madea has the best sense of humor, and the many funny lines, the stories ,and the cast, cannot be beat! Madea was a 'ho' at one time but if you listen to Tyler's messages, she gets in those digs that are sound and brilliant, and Godly. I hope to God that Tyler Perry doesn't put Madea to rest or I'm going to call 1-800-CHOKE-THAT-HO! LOL! She's a one bad 'dame,' but Joe claims she is a DUDE! LOL! Love it! Hallellujer!!!

text: Tyler Perry, you've been playing Madea as a source of tough love,  comedy, badassry, life lessons and more for as long as I can remember. Thank you, for all you've done for us fans/watches of both your plays and movies. Thank you for your works on OWN, and for bringing such joy to us old and new generations. If this is the end of Madea then I won't judge, criticize or curse you out on any social media. I may not know what it's like to be a famous playwright, actor or director, but I do know what it's like to be human and to want to have a break. So if you think it's time for Madea to go, then I will cry right now and learn to accept this sad fate, but by March 1st I'll be smiling and sending Madea off with a "Hallelu-Yer" until then! Thank you for being in my 21 (almost 22) years of my life as the crazy aunt-mother-grandmother-stripper-jailbird-countretto boss woman that we all know and love. God bless you forever for your teachings and stories. Thank you ðŸ˜ŠðŸ™ðŸ¾â¤ï¸  P.S.   I hope none of you take offense to me calling Madea a  aunt-mother-grandmother-stripper-jailbird-countretto. text: I don't care what color your skin is... FUNNY IS FUNNY!  And let's be real here.... those of us from the south, again regardless of color,  all know someone who reminds us of Madea, just maybe not as hard core LMBO.   Not too long ago I got the "you do realize that it's a black movie right" from a young black guy when buying tickets for a Madea movie. My response was  "well bless your heart. Thank you but I know what I want to see."  He rolled his eyes but before he said anything it was at this point my husband walked up,  and the ticket seller said "oh I see. no wonder" and shook his head.   I was ready to pull a Madea then!  I said,  "You see what? My gorgeous husband who happens to be black and cherokee and then you see me and think just because I am white and cherokee that he's the only reason I'm going to see this movie? Please tell me you're  really not that kind of special stupid! First of all, I am a grown ass southern woman. Ain't nobody but my mama or God going to tell me what to do or even what to watch. Second of all,  don't pull the race card on me when you are part of the damn problem. Trying to say it's a black movie like that means something. A good movie is a good movie.  And didn't you know God loves variety and that's why he made us all in these beautiful colors.  Just like if the earth was a crayola box and we're the crayons, and yes white is a color too.  You kid need a check up from the neck up and buy a clue or borrow a vowel because you just flipped my b*tch switch."  Now,  I didn't mean to go off like that nor did I realize how loud I got.  But he hit me on the anniversary of my mama's passing and I was in desperate need of a laugh.  My mama who told me that even though we have a  colorful family (there's six races in my family), there had been  rough times and not everyone would be OK with me dating my husband (which we have had not one problem though we have had two black and two white elderly people say that it wasn't for them and they wouldn't but if we were happy then go for it)  then two weeks after meeting him told me he was the one and if I didn't marry him she was going to divorce me and adopt him and who loved watching Madea too.  Needless to say the manager came over and asked if there was a problem and the ticket seller said he didn't need this bs and how he was just trying to help me.  SMH.  I just told the manager that it was a misunderstanding but  that he needs to remind his employees that movies are for everyone of any color.   I finally got my laugh, and then some, and maybe going off helped too because I sure felt better when leaving. I was still sad, still hurting,  but I didn't feel like I was being ripped apart inside as much if that makes sense. I told what happened to me so maybe someone else reading it would think twice before assuming. We got too much real trouble to worry about then the wrapping that is on the outside of another member of OUR race....the human race.  Thanks to whomever  is reading this! Most of all, Thank you Mr. Tyler Perry for sharing your gift with the world and for bringing smiles, laughs,  and some common Madea--sense to humans of all colors.
author: Dorie Pope Stephens
